1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 {My decision to choose this move mainly comes from the fact
that in case of 2...Nf6 3. Bg2 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 White has a wide range
of ideas and, overall, Black's position is not really in my taste. On the
other hand, I have a lot of confidence in 2...c6 and the move is very
challenging. It is obvious that Black's intention is to continue with 3...d5
gaining space in the center. White has a choice here and I will cover the
three main options 3.Nf3, 3.d4 and 3.Bg2} 3. Nf3 {Recently this move has
become quite fashionable. Actually, the position resembles the Alapin
variation in the Sicilian with the extra move g3 included.} e4 4. Nd4 d5 5.
cxd5 ({I don't think} 5. Bg2 $6 {is a serious move. Black is doing great after}
dxc4 $1 6. Nc2 Nf6 7. Nc3 {when Black has a choice. I prefer} Na6 8. Nxe4 Nxe4
9. Bxe4 Nc5 10. Bg2 Be6 11. Ne3 Qa5 12. O-O {Scherer, M (2325)-Tischbierek, R 
(2477) Altenkirchen 2005 and now very strong would have been} O-O-O $146 13.
Qc2 Qb5 $1 {when it is not clear how White is going to develop his queenside.
For instance,} 14. Rd1 ({or} 14. f4 g6 15. f5 gxf5 16. Nxf5 Nd3 $1 $17 {
with threats such as Bxf5 and Qc5, white is in big problems.}) 14... g6 15. d3
cxd3 16. exd3 Bg7 {and Black's positional advantage is beyond any doubts.}) ({
Alternatively,} 5. d3 {is quite an interesting try. We have seen several
GM-level games recently.} Bc5 {this has only occurred in two games but it seems
to be the best move.} 6. Nb3 Bb4+ {The point of Bc5 first was to kick
white knight away from the central square (d4).} 7. Bd2 Bxd2+ 8. Qxd2 {Now I
think Black should choose} dxc4 ({Black failed to equalize after} 8... exd3 9.
Qxd3 dxc4 10. Qxc4 Be6 ({A better try would have been} 10... Nf6 11. Bg2 O-O {
although I still prefer White after} 12. O-O Re8 13. N1d2 {His kingside
majority (plan with e4,f4,e5 etc.) looks more potent than black's queenside
majority.}) 11. Qc2 Na6 12. Bg2 Nf6 $2 13. Bxc6+ $1 bxc6 14. Qxc6+ Bd7 15. Qxa6
$16 {White was much better in Tazbir,M (2517)-Navara,D (2744) Poland 2016}) 9.
dxc4 {Here I have a new idea} f5 $5 $146 {which, in my opinion, improves over
the game. One exemplary line would be} (9... Qxd2+ 10. N1xd2 f5 11. c5 (11. f3
$142 $1 {would give White a better game, for example:} Nf6 12. Bg2 exf3 13.
exf3 O-O 14. O-O-O $14 {The move f5 really weakened black's position and he
will face difficulties with dark squares such as e5, e7, and d6.}) 11... Nf6 12.
e3 g6 13. Nc4 Ke7 14. Nd6 Nbd7 {and Black was doing perfectly fine in Salem, A 
(2633) -Hammer, J (2621) Moscow 2017. The knight on d6 is not as dangerous as
it seems at the first glance. It is disconnected from the rest of White's
undeveloped forces.}) 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 11. Nc3 Nf6 12. Nd4 g6 13. O-O-O Nbd7 14.
f3 Re8 $11 {with equality. Both sides have virtually no weaknesses.}) 5... Qxd5
6. Nc2 {This has been White's most popular choice recently.} Nf6 7. Nc3 Qe5 8.
Bg2 {That is the main continuation.} ({White has tried two other moves} 8. d4
exd3 9. Qxd3 Bf5 10. Qe3 Qxe3 11. Nxe3 Be6 {with a balanced endgame Duda, J 
(2666)-Yilmaz, M (2603) Gjakova 2016. Black can complete his development
effortlessly with Bc5, 0-0, Nbd7, etc.}) ({And} 8. b3 {which seems too slow
and Black obtained a very nice position after} Bc5 9. Bg2 Bf5 10. Bb2 Qe7 11.
Ne3 Bg6 12. Qc2 Nbd7 {Kovalenko,I (2680)-Mikhalevski,V (2528) Tallinn 2016.
Many ideas are possible for both sides, but it is important to keep in mind
not to give away any central squares for free.}) 8... Be7 9. Ne3 ({White was
not successful at all in the following game} 9. O-O O-O 10. f4 $6 {A possible,
but somewhat dubious approach to solving the issue of e4 pawn.} exf3 11. Rxf3
c5 $1 {The key. Black is not allowing white to expand with d4.} 12. Ne3 Nc6 13.
Qf1 Nd4 {with a nice advantage for Black in Grandelius, N (2649) -Giri, A (2790)
Stavanger 2016}) 9... Na6 10. Qc2 Nb4 11. Qb1 Be6 12. b3 Nbd5 13. Bb2 Nxe3 14.
fxe3 Bf5 15. O-O Qe6 {Black solved his opening problems Hammer, J (2651)-Navara,
D (2742) Novy Bor 2016. As long as black can keep the e4-pawn under control and
white pieces cramped, he has nothing to worry about.} *

