1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. Nf3 e4 4. Nd4 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 {White's two alternatives
are also very important:} 6. e3 (6. Nb3 Nf6 7. Bg2 ({Very harmless is
considered to be} 7. Nc3 Qh5 8. h3 ({The other moves are} 8. d3 exd3 9. Qxd3 {
Black's play in the following example is very convincing} Na6 10. Nd4 Nb4 11.
Qe3+ Be7 12. a3 Nbd5 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. Qe4 O-O 15. Bg2 Bf6 {and Black was
clearly better in Larsen, B (2560)-Gulko, B (2590) Hastings 1988. White's
development problems are palpable.}) ({It is important to mention that} 8. Bg2
{runs into} Bh3 $1 {and Black is obviously doing great after} 9. O-O Bxg2 10.
Kxg2 Na6 {followed up by 11...0-0-0}) 8... a5 9. d3 {this occurred in Norri,J 
(2421)-Elsness, F (2461) Finland 2004 and now I would recommend the natural}
exd3 $146 10. Qxd3 Na6 $1 {and Black is doing great, for instance} 11. Bg2 Nb4
12. Qd1 Be6 $1 {with the following nice idea} 13. a3 Rd8 14. Bd2 Nd3+ $1 15.
exd3 Qxd1+ 16. Nxd1 Bxb3 17. Bxa5 Rxd3 {and Black is most probably
symbolically better. However, the absence of serious weaknesses in white's
position makes a draw the most likely outcome.}) 7... Qh5 {As usual, black is
looking to exchange the light-squared bishops in order to relieve the pressure
of the e4 pawn as well as to create light-squared weaknesses in white's
position.} 8. h3 (8. Nc3 {see 7. о ..c3}) 8... Qg6 9. Nc3 Na6 10. d3 exd3 11.
O-O ({Much worse is} 11. e4 $143 Be6 12. O-O {Rukavina, J (2422)-Stojanovic, M 
(2506) Interlaken 2003} (12. Qxd3 {runs into} Nb4 13. Qe2 Nxa2 $1 {Black wins
a pawn.}) {now Black should have played} 12... Rd8 $1 $17 {it is hard to
imagine that White has anything for being pawn down.}) 11... Bb4 12. e4 ({
This is better than} 12. Qxd3 Qxd3 13. exd3 Nc5 14. Nxc5 Bxc5 15. Bg5 Be6 $15 {
Black has a better endgame due to White's backward pawn, Chomet, P (2350)
-Degraeve,J (2540) Saint Affrique 2006}) 12... O-O 13. Qxd3 {this all happened
in Gulko,B (2490)-Vasiukov,E (2480) Moscow 1983 when Black should have
continuedwith} Re8 $1 $146 14. Rd1 h6 {with comfortable position. White can
only achieve an advantage in this type of pawn structure if he gets to push
his kingside majority. However, black has just enough pressure against the e4
pawn here (pending Bxc3), so white has no way of completing this plan.}) 6...
Bc5 7. Nc3 Qe5 8. Bg2 ({Not dangerous for Black is} 8. Nb3 Bb6 9. d4 exd3 10.
Qxd3 Nf6 11. Bg2 O-O 12. Qe2 {Kjartansson,G (2446)-Grandelius,N (2646)
Reykjavik 2016 and now most probably the best idea would have been} Bg4 $1 $146
13. f3 Be6 14. O-O Nd5 $15 {with very nice play for Black.}) 8... Nf6 9. O-O {
The main continuation.} ({In order to avoid Black's 9...о Pxd4 possibility a
more precise move order for White would have been} 9. d3 $142 exd3 10. Qxd3 O-O
11. O-O {transposing to 9.0-0}) ({White other options are not impressive at all
} 9. Nde2 O-O 10. O-O Rd8 11. Qc2 Bf5 {is obviously better for Black in Haag, M
(2267) -Petrov, N (2493) Arco 2016, due to central superiority thanks to the e4
pawn.}) (9. f4 Qe7 10. Nde2 h5 {Explain.} 11. h3 Bf5 $15 {is very nice for
Black as well Heberla, B (2516)-Semcesen, D (2433) Wroclaw 2010. White should
try to avoid such positions as his pieces (especially knights) lack good
squares.}) 9... O-O ({It seems as if Black can play} 9... Bxd4 $5 $146 10. exd4
Qxd4 11. Re1 ({Or} 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Bxe4 O-O) 11... O-O 12. Nxe4 Nbd7 {
with a solid game for Black in both cases. White's bishop pair can hardly make
an impact with the burden of an isolated d-pawn.}) 10. d3 exd3 11. Qxd3 Na6 12.
a3 {White has been doing pretty well in this position, but I believe Black has
a very reliable position and I can offer the following new idea:} Qh5 $5 $146 {
I checked two options for White} 13. Nde2 (13. b4 Bxd4 14. Qxd4 Bh3 15. Rd1
Bxg2 16. Kxg2 Nc7 {with balanced play. White has some long-term trumps like a
potentially strong dark-squared bishop, but black is just extremely solid.})
13... Ng4 14. h3 ({Or} 14. h4 {Some might wonder why the caveman-like g7-g5 is
not an option.} Ne5 (14... g5 $5 {looks very tempting, but white survives with}
15. f3 $1) 15. Qe4 Re8 16. Nf4 Qg4 $11) 14... Ne5 15. Qe4 Re8 16. g4 Qg6 17.
Qxg6 Nxg6 $11 {in both cases with an equal game. The knight on the rim can get
into the game via c7. Black also has an annoying Nh4 resource.} *

