1. g3 e5 2. Bg2 Nf6 3. c4 c6 4. Nc3 d5 5. cxd5 (5. d4 e4 {would transpose to
the 4.d4 line.}) 5... cxd5 {This old line is considered to be great for Black
and it is hard to find too many games played by strong players here nowadays.}
6. Qb3 {The most challenging move:} (6. d4 exd4 7. Qxd4 {would be a good idea
if Black's pawn could not move to d4 with tempo.} Nc6 8. Qd1 d4 $1 9. Ne4 Be7 {
Most probably Black has something more challenging but this simple approach is
good enough at least for a very comfortable game} 10. Nxf6+ Bxf6 11. Nh3 $1 ({
Black is better after} 11. Nf3 O-O 12. O-O Re8 $1 {as occurred in several games.
This is a great version of the Tarrasch IQP type of position where the
"isolani" has reached the fourth rank, fixing the backward pawn on the
neighboring file (e2).}) 11... O-O 12. O-O Re8 13. Nf4 Bf5 {and Black has no
problems whatsoever Sapi, L-Bilek, I Budapest 1963.}) 6... Nc6 $1 {A well-known
pawn sacrifice.} ({Obviously White hopes for} 6... e4 7. d3 {fighting for the
advantage.}) 7. Nxd5 ({White can reject the central pawn by means of} 7. d3 {
which is definitely harmless though. I like the following new idea} d4 8. Nd5
Nd7 $5 $146 {all nine games here went 8...Nxd5} 9. e4 Bd6 10. Nf3 Nc5 11.
Qc2 a5 12. O-O O-O {with a nice game for Black. His space advantage gives him
good prospects in the upcoming battle.}) 7... Nd4 {The point behind Black's
previous move.} 8. Nxf6+ gxf6 $5 ({This move is considered to be more
aggressive compared with} 8... Qxf6 {, which should be a reasonable
alternative.}) 9. Qd1 ({Not playable for White is} 9. Qd3 $2 Qc7 10. Kf1 {
Rueckleben,H (2124)-Reichenbach,W (2347) Dresden 2006} Bf5 $1 $146 {is the
most simple here} 11. Be4 Be6 {with large advantage. White's development is
awkward and difficult to complete, mainly due to the powerful knight on d4.})
9... Qc7 10. Rb1 (10. Be4 {stopping Nc2 fork} f5 11. Bb1 Be6 $17) (10. Kf1 {
This usually is White's first choice.} Be6 11. b3 Nc2 (11... O-O-O {might be a
decent alternative, for example} 12. d3 Kb8 13. Bb2 {Bezold-Erdos, Germany
2017 here Black should have played something like} Qb6 $146 14. Nf3 Nxf3 15.
Bxf3 Bc5 {with good, sufficient compensation. Black may not claim an advantage,
but white definitely faces some difficulties in development.}) 12. Rb1 {
leads to the main line.}) 10... Nc2+ 11. Kf1 Be6 12. b3 Rc8 {After a sequence
of pretty forced moves White has some choice} 13. Bb2 ({The logical
alternative is} 13. Nf3 Na3 14. Ra1 (14. Bxa3 Bxa3 {definitely gives Black a
lot of compensation, at the very least due to the bishop pair.}) {and Black
has at least} 14... Nc2 15. Rb1 Na3 {with a repetition.}) 13... Ba3 14. Nf3 ({
White has other options:} 14. Bc3 Nb4 15. Bxb4 Bxb4 16. Nf3 O-O 17. Ne1 Rfd8
$15 {and Black was definitely better in Hodgson-Illescas Cordoba, Wijk aan Zee
1993}) ({and} 14. Be4 Bxb2 15. Rxb2 Na3 $1 {Kind of trapping the rook on b2!}
16. e3 f5 17. Bg2 O-O $1 ({Black could have maintained the balance with the
natural} 17... e4 $5 18. Ne2 Qe5 19. d4 exd3 20. Nd4 Nc2 $1 {It is essential
to trade off the powerful knight on d4.} 21. Qxd3 Nxd4 22. Qxd4 Qb5+ 23. Ke1
O-O $44 {but it seems Black is striving for more}) 18. Nf3 Rfd8 19. d4 Nb5 {
and Black took over in 0-1 (41) MacGregor-Price ICCF email 2010. White was not
able to complete his development satisfactorily, while black is already fully
prepared for the fight in the center.}) 14... O-O 15. Ne1 Bxb2 16. Rxb2 Nxe1
17. Kxe1 {this occurred in Bandow-Morawietz, Bad Wiessee 2011 Black should have
played} ({or} 17. Qxe1 Qc1 18. Rb1 Qc2 $36 {and Black keeps the initiative.})
17... Qc1 $1 $146 18. Rb1 Qa3 {and Black has definitely a lot in return for
being a pawn down. White's position is very dangerous. Let us not forget that
in this position it would be illegal for white to castle! That's why it looks
virtually impossible to include the h1 rook into the game. In such
circumstances, white's extra pawn is irrelevant (one might even argue that
black needs the semi-open file more than a pawn on that file!).} *

