1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. d4 e4 {Black is trying to build up a pawn chain in the
center with d7-d5.} 4. Nc3 d5 5. Nh3 {This is quite a tricky move which
requires Black to play very precisely.} ({A very important line here is} 5.
cxd5 cxd5 6. Qb3 Nc6 $1 {It goes without saying Black would be worse if it
were not for this move.} (6... Nf6 7. Bg5 {is very annoying.}) 7. Qxd5 ({
White has to enter complications since after} 7. e3 Nf6 {Black is just better
thanks to his space superiority.}) 7... Qxd5 8. Nxd5 Nxd4 9. Nc7+ Kd8 10. Nxa8
Nc2+ 11. Kd1 Nxa1 {After a sequence of pretty forced moves White has to fight
for equality since the e4-pawn seriously hurts White's development.} 12. Bf4 $1
{I believe this is the only move where White maintains the balance. The other
moves are better for Black:} (12. Bh3 Bc5 13. Bg5+ {as happened in Suba,M 
(2487)-Mikhalevski, V (2597) Benidorm 2008 and now Black should have played} Ne7
$146 {when the play could have continued} 14. Kc1 f6 15. Bd2 Bxf2 16. Bg2 Bf5
17. Nh3 Bc5 $17 {Black has emerged from the complications up a pawn. Both
knights are getting trapped in the corner, which does not change the material
balance.}) (12. Be3 Be6 13. Bxa7 ({Other options include:} 13. b3 Nxb3 $1 14.
axb3 Bxb3+ 15. Kc1 Ba3+ 16. Kd2 {this all occurred in Solak, D (2567)-Volokitin,
A (2645) Murska Sobota 2006 now the most precise would have been} Nf6 $1 $146 {
White is currently up a piece, but the main issue in the position is the
weakness of his king, which is amplified by the fact that his whole kingside
is undeveloped. On the other hand, black develops quickly and achieves a
strong attack. The following sample line proves this point:} 17. Kc3 Ba2 18.
Bxa7 Nd5+ 19. Kd2 Ke7 20. Nb6 Rd8 21. Nxd5+ Rxd5+ 22. Kc2 b5 $1 $19 {with a
decisive advantage.}) ({and} 13. Bh3 Bxa2 14. Bxa7 Bb4 $1 {This is the best
square for the bishop by far as it controls important squares e1 and d2.} 15.
e3 {Gerber,R (2393)-Raetsky,A (2430) Lenk 2011} ({Much worse is} 15. Bb6+ $143
Ke7 16. Nc7 Nf6 $19 {and White is just lost, Marin,I (2261)-Ikonomopoulou,M 
(2050) Plovdiv 2008.}) 15... h5 $1 $146 {looks like the best option for Black}
16. Ne2 Rh6 17. Bb6+ Ke7 18. Nc3 Bc4 $17 {Black is clearly better as white
plays without a rook and also has to constantly watch out to threats to his
king's safety.}) 13... Bxa2 14. e3 (14. Bh3 Bb4 {transpose to 13. о Ph3}) 14...
Bb4 15. Ne2 Nf6 16. Bh3 Ke7 17. Nb6 Rd8+ 18. Nd4 Ke8 $1 19. Ke2 Nc2 $1 20. Rd1
Nxd4+ 21. Rxd4 Bc5 22. Rxd8+ Kxd8 {White was far from equality in Rakovic, M 
(2259)-Pascual Perez, N (2314) LSS email 2008, despite apparent symmetry in the
position. His pieces are utterly uncoordinated, unlike their black
counterparts.}) {The following game is very convincing} 12... Be6 13. b3 Nxb3
$1 14. axb3 Bxb3+ 15. Kc1 Ba3+ 16. Kb1 Ne7 17. e3 g5 $5 {Deflecting the bishop
from h2-b8 diagonal, which leaves the a8 knight without c7 square.} 18. Bxg5
Kd7 19. Bh3+ Be6 20. Bxe6+ fxe6 21. Bxe7 Bxe7 22. Ne2 Rxa8 23. Rd1+ Ke8 24. Rd4
{with a very complex, but objectively balanced endgame De Bari, V (2373)
-Penafiel Lopez, J (2350) ICCF email 2009. Black's passed queenside pawns are
definitely a force to be reckoned with, but since they have not yet advanced
past the seventh rank, white will have enough time to block them.}) (5. Qb3 {
has been played only twice in practice. In my opinion, the main reason White
has been rejecting this move is due to} dxc4 $1 $146 6. Qxc4 Be6 7. Qa4 f5 8.
Nh3 Nf6 {and Black should be very comfortable thanks to his e4-pawn.}) (5. f3 {
deserves some attention. Black should respond} Nf6 {until now we have only one
game here, which saw} 6. Bg5 Bb4 7. Bg2 Nbd7 $1 {An important move before
h7-h6, so that we can take back with the knight.} 8. fxe4 dxe4 9. Nh3 h6 {
and Black is perfectly fine Lievre, V (1938)-Masset, J (2035) Survilliers 2013})
5... Bb4 6. Qb3 {The most challenging.} ({Very easy for Black is} 6. Bg2 Nf6 7.
O-O O-O {for example:} 8. cxd5 cxd5 (8... Bxc3 $5 {is worthy of consideration}
9. bxc3 cxd5 10. f3 h6 $1 {A prohylactic move against the annoying Bg5.} 11.
Nf4 Nc6 12. fxe4 dxe4 13. Ba3 Re8 {and Black is fine Roth,M (2195)-Meschke,A 
(2215) Pforzheim 1999. The pawn on e4 restricts white's possibilities
considerably.}) 9. Qb3 Bxc3 10. bxc3 (10. Qxc3 h6 $1 {also looks more pleasant
for Black.}) 10... h6 11. f3 {this has been reached in Petrosian, T (2643)
-Hovhannisyan,R (2600) Dubai 2012 now Black should have continued with normal
development} Nc6 $1 $146 12. Nf2 Na5 13. Qb1 exf3 14. exf3 Re8 {and Black is
at least not worse. The backward pawn on c3 is not yet a source of worries for
white, but he must play actively to compensate for this structural defect.})
6... a5 $1 {A very important move, Black delays the capture on c3 and tries to
provoke a3. In many lines inclusion of these moves gives black additional
strategic motives, such as playing against light-squared weaknesses c4 and b3 
(after a5-a4!).} 7. cxd5 ({It's very important to mention that for the time
being White cannot play} 7. a3 $2 {in view of} dxc4 8. Qxc4 Be6 $1 {and White
loses material.}) ({It is hard to imagine that} 7. c5 {as occurred in Vovk,
Y-Messinger, Marseille 2013 can pose Black any problems. I would suggest the
following idea for Black} b6 $146 8. a3 Bxc3+ 9. Qxc3 Nf6 10. Bg2 Ba6 {with a
nice game for Black.}) 7... cxd5 8. Bg2 ({Now White also tried} 8. a3 {but
after} Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 (9. Qxc3 Nc6 {is also fine for Black. He will continue
Nge7, castle and Bf5 with full control over important squares.}) 9... a4 10.
Qb5+ Nc6 11. Bd2 {Klekowski,M (2478)-Navara,D (2728) Germany 2015 Black should
have better continued with} Nge7 $146 12. Nf4 O-O 13. Bg2 Ra6 $1 $15 {with a
better game. The aforementioned light-squared strategy will soon come into
full effect (Na5-Nc4(b3) etc.).}) 8... Nc6 9. Nf4 Nf6 10. O-O {this position
happened in Vishnu-Kohlweyer, Gibraltar 2016, here I found the following
improvement} a4 $5 $146 {with two possible lines} 11. Nxa4 ({and} 11. Qd1 Bxc3
{creating a backward pawn on c3 and a cozy square on c4.} 12. bxc3 O-O 13. Rb1
Re8 14. f3 Na5 {with a complex middlegame position. Both sides have certain
positional advantages and disadvantages. White will most likely try to play on
the dark squares, while black would most certainly play on the light-squares.})
11... Qa5 (11... g5 $5 {deserves attention} 12. Nh3 h6 $44 {with interesting
compensation. White has two knights on the rim and has problems with piece
coordination.}) 12. Nc3 Nxd4 13. Qd1 Bxc3 14. bxc3 Ne6 15. Be3 O-O 16. Qd2 Bd7
17. Rfb1 Bc6 $11 {Black is extremely solid, with well-positioned pieces.} *

