1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. d4 e4 4. d5 {A logical try to split Black central pawns.}
Bb4+ 5. Bd2 ({Very few games saw} 5. Nc3 {and it's understandable since
besides} Nf6 {which probably should transpose to our main line after} (5...
Bxc3+ $5 $146 6. bxc3 Nf6 7. Bg2 ({not dangerous for Black is} 7. Ba3 cxd5 (
7... d6 8. dxc6 Nxc6 9. Bxd6 e3 $1 {is also interesting - to ruin white's pawn
structure on both ends.}) 8. cxd5 Qc7 $1 9. Qd4 d6 10. Bg2 O-O {Black is
better.}) 7... d6 8. Bg5 Bf5 {with excellent game for black as it does not
look like white has a good way to compensate for his bad pawn structure.}) 6.
Bd2 Qe7) 5... Qe7 6. Nc3 {Main move. Only one game saw} (6. e3 {Lazic-Pap,
SRB-ch 2010 Black should have strengthened his center by means of} f5 $146 7.
a3 Bxd2+ (7... Bd6 {also deserves attention}) 8. Qxd2 d6 {with a good
position for Black. The plan is to bring the knight to e5 with a positional
edge.}) 6... Nf6 7. Bg2 ({The alternative here is} 7. a3 {A top-level continued
} Bxc3 8. Bxc3 d6 9. Nh3 cxd5 10. cxd5 O-O 11. Bg2 Bf5 $1 12. O-O Nbd7 13. Nf4
h6 {and Black has solved his opening problems Ding-Anand, Bilbao 2015. The
arising position is complicated and imbalanced: white bishop's pair is
compensated by Black active pieces.}) 7... O-O 8. Nh3 ({Other continuations are
} 8. a3 Bxc3 9. Bxc3 cxd5 10. cxd5 d6 11. Nh3 Bf5 {and this position is
covered in 7. a3}) ({and} 8. e3 cxd5 9. cxd5 Bxc3 10. Bxc3 d6 11. Ne2 Nbd7 12.
O-O Re8 13. Bxf6 ({I also checked} 13. Rc1 {in this case Black shouldn't rush
with 13...Ne5, but rather choose} a5 $5 (13... Ne5 14. Bxe5 $1 Qxe5 15. Qd4
Bg4 16. Qxe5 Rxe5 17. Nc3 {and Black is doomed to defending inferior endgame.})
) 13... Nxf6 14. Nc3 {this occurred in Bokros-Cibickova, Dunajska Streda 2017 I
would suggest here} Qe5 $146 15. h3 b6 {with complicated game, where Black has a fully adequate play. d5 is potentially weak and black can continue either
Ba6-d3 or simply Bb7 followed by doubling the rooks on the c-file.}) 8... cxd5
9. cxd5 d6 10. Nxe4 {This seems to be the right moment for White to force
simplifications,} ({since after} 10. O-O Bf5 $1 {White can easily end up in an inferior position, as it happened in the following game} 11. a3 Bc5 12. Bg5
Nbd7 13. Na4 h6 14. Bxf6 {this all occurred in Von Bahr-Palac, Split 2015 after
natural} Nxf6 $1 {Black is clearly better.} 15. Nxc5 dxc5 16. d6 Qd7 {would
provide an easy target and black would soon be up a pawn.}) 10... Bxh3 11.
Nxf6+ Qxf6 12. Bxh3 Qxb2 13. Bxb4 Qxb4+ 14. Qd2 Qxd2+ 15. Kxd2 Na6 {After a
pretty forced sequence of moves we reached a balanced endgame with dynamic
possibilities for both sides. The following high-level game is very important
for thisline} 16. e4 Nc5 17. Rhe1 Rae8 {it is essential for black to obstruct
white's plan f4-e5.} 18. f3 Re5 19. Re2 g6 20. Bg2 f5 21. f4 Nxe4+ 22. Bxe4
Rxe4 {and draw was agreed in Ivanchuk-Gelfand, Wijk aan Zee 2008} *

