1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. d4 e4 4. Nc3 d5 5. Bg2 {Main line} Nf6 6. cxd5 ({After} 6.
Bg5 Nbd7 {and white has nothing better than} 7. cxd5 cxd5 {transposing to 6.
cxd5}) 6... cxd5 7. Bg5 {It's hard to imagine that White can challenge Black
position with other moves. I would rather mention one recent example} (7. Nh3
Bb4 8. O-O Bxc3 $5 ({though there is nothing wrong with} 8... O-O) 9. bxc3 O-O
10. f3 exf3 11. Rxf3 h6 $5 12. Qf1 Nbd7 13. a4 {Aronian-Anand, Doha 2016 and
now natural-looking} Ne4 14. Nf2 Ndf6 {would secure Black positional
superiority. The control over e4 square is very important in such structures.})
7... Nbd7 8. Qb3 {White's most popular and in my opinion the most challenging
attempt. Other moves here:} (8. Qa4 {White's second choice according to the
theory, but it's hardly impressive after accurate} Qb6 $1 {attacking b2 pawn.}
9. Qb5 {Black is doing great after} (9. Bd2 {Now black should not take the
pawn on b2, but there is also no pressure on f6 anymore, so he can simply
complete his development.} Be7 10. Nh3 O-O 11. Nf4 Qd6 12. Qb3 Nb6 $15 {
Jirovsky-Navara, Czechia 2014}) 9... Bb4 10. Qxb6 {now I like intermediate}
Bxc3+ $1 $146 {which hasn't been played} 11. bxc3 axb6 12. Nh3 h6 13. Bf4 Ra3 {
and Black has a good game thanks to active play against white's weak pawns.}) (
8. e3 h6 9. Bf4 (9. Bxf6 Nxf6 10. Nge2 Bd6 11. Qb3 {see 9.e3}) {Adams,M-Bogner,
Germany 2013 Black should have choosen} 9... Nb6 10. Nge2 Bd6 {completing
development with comfortable position.}) (8. f3 h6 $1 {White has a problem
with his dark-squared bishop} 9. Bxf6 {not impressive} (9. Bc1 Bb4 10. Nh3 O-O
11. Nf2 Re8 $17 {and White's strategy obviously has failed Micheli-Hilverda,
Austria 2016}) (9. Bf4 Bb4 10. Qb3 Qe7 11. Bd2 {all this occurred in Donchenko,
A-Mastrovasilis, D Legnica 2013 a very strong idea would have been} a5 $1 $146
12. a3 Bxc3 13. Bxc3 O-O {with great position for Black. We discussed in a
previous chapter how the inclusion of a3 and a5 moves usually favors black.}) (
9. Be3 Bb4 10. Qb3 Qe7 {White has problems with his kingside development} 11.
Kf2 $2 {terrible move Kovalenko-Efanov, Minsk 2015 after} O-O $146 {Black's
position seems winning to me. White's development looks ridiculous.}) 9...
Nxf6 10. fxe4 dxe4 11. Nxe4 Bb4+ 12. Nc3 O-O 13. Nf3 Nd5 {with excellent
compensation for the pawn in the form of strong play on the dark squares.})
8... Bd6 9. Nh3 ({Obviously the central pawn is untouchable} 9. Nxd5 $2 Qa5+ $1
{when white is losing one of his minor pieces.}) ({The only reasonable
alternative is} 9. e3 h6 10. Bxf6 Nxf6 11. Nge2 {Gagare-Dragun, Pune 2014 I
like the following solution for Black} b6 $5 12. O-O Bb7 {and Black should be
just fine considering his space advantage. After white undermines his pawn
chain with f3, the bishop will give support to the central pawn from the b7
square.}) 9... h6 10. Bf4 Nb6 11. Be5 $5 {White's latest word in this line.}
Nh5 $1 {An amazing move, which seems to be solving Black's opening problems
relatively easily. The key is not to allow white knight on h3 to join the
fight for the center.} 12. Bxd6 {Other moves:} (12. Nb5 Bxe5 13. dxe5 O-O 14.
O-O Be6 15. Nf4 Nxf4 16. gxf4 Nc4 17. Rfd1 Qb6 {Black successfully equalized
in Krause-Grebenshchikov, ICCF email 2014. White's bishop is actually quite
passive in this structure.}) (12. f3 Bxe5 13. dxe5 {Peschke-Kosic, ICCF email
2013 my idea here is to continue} O-O $146 14. fxe4 dxe4 15. Nxe4 Be6 $44 {
with sufficient compensation as the e5 pawn will probably not survive there
for too long.}) ({And finally} 12. O-O O-O 13. Nf4 Nxf4 14. gxf4 Bg4 $1 {
an aggressive move.} 15. Nxd5 $6 Bxe5 16. Nxb6 Bxf4 17. Nxa8 Qg5 $40 {and Black
attack was decisive in Ziese-Tyulenko, ICCF email 2012}) 12... Qxd6 13. Nb5 Qc6
14. Qb4 Be6 15. O-O (15. Nd6+ {achieves absolutely nothing for white. Black
king is safe on} Kd7) 15... a5 $1 16. Qc5 Kd7 {very unusual play, but it works
well!} 17. Nc3 (17. Rfc1 Na4 $1 {is excellent for black:} 18. Qxc6+ bxc6 $17)
17... f5 18. Rfc1 Rhc8 {and Black was already better in Boschma-Kosic, ICCF
email 2012.} *

