1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 e5 3. g3 Bb4 4. Nf3 Bxc3 $1 {We definitely don't want to play
4...Nc6 switching to main theoretical line of English four knights.} 5. bxc3 (
5. dxc3 {is the other recapture. Here the play goes} d6 6. Bg2 h6 7. O-O Nc6 8.
Qc2 ({Other moves are:} 8. b3 {here I believe it's important for Black to start
} Bf5 $1 {in order to prevent possible e2-e4 move} 9. Ne1 (9. Nd2 {would run
into} e4 $1) 9... Qd7 10. f3 {this happened in Dimovski-Ristic, Bela Crkva
1986 certainly Black should have played} e4 $1 $146 11. Nc2 Bh3 {with nice
game.}) (8. h3 {allows Black to develop aggressive play} Be6 9. b3 Qd7 10. Kh2
O-O-O 11. Be3 {Maslak-Kuznetsov, Pardubice 2017 and now logical follow up of
Black strategy would have} Kb8 $146 {with approximate line} 12. Ne1 Nh7 $1 13.
Nd3 Ng5 14. h4 Nh7 $1 $17 {and Black knight is heading to g4 with great effect.
}) (8. Ne1 {Black has never played} Bf5 $1 $146 {in this position. As I
mentioned above I find it's very important to prevent White's e4-move} 9. Nc2
Qd7 10. f3 e4 {and Black is doing great similar to the previous line.}) 8... Be6 9.
b3 Qd7 10. e4 Bh3 {Black has no problems after he exchanges a pair of
light-squared bishops. Here is the recently played model game} 11. Ne1 O-O 12.
f3 Nh7 13. Be3 b6 14. Rd1 Bxg2 15. Nxg2 f5 $15 {and Black slowly took over in
Ivanchuk-Giri, Leuven 2017}) 5... d6 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O Re8 {A relatively new
approach, supporting the e4 push.} 8. Ne1 {This seems like White's most
serious attempt. Other moves:} ({The main alternative} 8. d3 e4 $1 9. Nd4 h6 {
The model game here continued} 10. Rb1 Nbd7 11. h3 {Mamedov,R-Grigoriants,
Berlin 2015 Black should have played} Nc5 $146 12. f3 exd3 13. exd3 d5 14. Ba3
Ne6 {with equality as white will have to part with his powerful centralized
knight.}) (8. Rb1 e4 9. Nd4 Nbd7 10. Ba3 {probably is not the best idea. White
should better opted for} (10. d3 Nc5 11. f3 {although Black is perfectly fine
after} exd3 12. exd3 d5 $1) 10... Ne5 11. Qb3 {Machalova,V-Esposito,M Cannes
1997 after} c5 $1 $146 12. Nc2 Bg4 13. Rfe1 Rb8 {Black's positional advantage
is beyond any doubts. White's bishops lack operating space.}) ({Definitely not
a good idea} 8. d4 $6 {as it leaves c4-pawn quite vulnerable} e4 $1 9. Ne1 h6
10. Nc2 Nc6 11. Ne3 Na5 $15 {Black is better positionally Nitschke-Krumm, GER
email 2013}) 8... Nbd7 {here Black knight is more flexible to compared to
c6-square.} 9. Nc2 {White also tried} (9. e4 Nc5 10. d3 Bd7 $1 {Now Black plan
is very clear, he has to carry out b7-b5 break} 11. Nc2 {Levaux-Akl, France
2006 and now Black could have easily played} ({White cannot really stop Black
idea:} 11. a4 a6 12. a5 b5 13. axb6 cxb6 {following up by 14...b5}) 11... a6
$146 12. Ne3 b5 {with timely counterplay on the queenside, especially
considering the fact that white is getting ready for the kingside offensive
with f4, etc.}) 9... h6 10. Rb1 {This has been played in Svidler-Tari,
Khanty-Mansiysk 2017. Now I would suggest the following improvement upon the
game} ({I also examined} 10. e4 a6 {preparing b7-b5.} 11. a4 Nc5 12. d3 Bd7 13.
a5 b5 14. axb6 cxb6 {and Black has his own play on the queenside.}) 10... e4
$146 11. d3 Nb6 {with complicated middlegame, where Black looks very
comfortable. The knight on b6 serves as a blocking piece so that the b7 pawn
is not hanging after developing the bishop from c8. It also puts pressure on
white's c4 pawn. Black might play c7-c5 at the right moment, limiting white's
options in the center to an even greater extent.} *

