1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 Bb4 {We are not committing with Nc6 for now as d2-d4 is not a
threat and also because of the fact that in a case of Nc6 White has the annoying resource
Nc3-d5.} 4. Bg2 O-O 5. Nf3 Re8 {This is considered to be an improved version
for Black since he did not commit to the Nc6 move.} 6. O-O e4 7. Nd4 Nc6 8.
Nc2 {Obviously harmless} (8. Nxc6 dxc6 {just one example} 9. d3 exd3 10. exd3 {
Poldauf-Karasev, Leningrad 1990 a very logical improvement would have been} Bc5
$1 $146 11. Bg5 Bd4 {establishing control over d4-square.}) 8... Bxc3 9. dxc3 {
Another line} (9. bxc3 d5 10. cxd5 Qxd5 {here White has tried many moves. I
will examine the most important ones} 11. Ne3 {White's most popular move.
Other options:} ({This is considered as best by Ribli. But if Sammalvuo's new
idea holds up, then White will have to look for alternatives at this juncture.
The alternatives are:} 11. d3 Qh5 12. Ne3 Bh3 {Black is doing great} 13. d4 {
clealry bad for White} (13. dxe4 $6 Bxg2 14. Kxg2 Rxe4 15. Rb1 b6 $17 {was
clearly better for Black Sajtar-R.Fuchs, Leipzig 1965}) 13... Rad8 14. Rb1 b6
15. Qa4 Na5 16. Qb5 Qxb5 17. Rxb5 {Ipatov-Sokolov,I Dubai 2014 after} Be6 $1
$146 18. Rb2 h6 {and the arising endgame is clearly more pleasant for Black
due to the well-known domination on the light-squares.}) (11. d4 {This is a
brand new idea, and it appears a rather effective one.} Qh5 12. f3 (12. Ne3 {
see 11. о ..e3}) 12... exf3 13. exf3 Na5 {heading to c4-square} 14. Ne3 {
this has been played in Gobleja-Krajnc, ICCF email 2004 now simple} Be6 $146
15. f4 Qxd1 16. Rxd1 c6 {and I would rather prefer Black.}) ({Finally dubious
is} 11. f3 $6 Qc5+ $1 12. Kh1 exf3 13. Rxf3 Bg4 14. Rxf6 gxf6 15. Ne3 Rxe3 $1 {
Black returns the favor by counter-sacrificing the exchange in order to
destroy white's most active piece and his pawn structure in the process.} 16.
dxe3 Rd8 $17 {Black was strategically winning in Ubilava-Rashkovsky, Kujbyshev
1986}) 11... Qh5 {and here several things have been tried:} 12. Rb1 {other
moves have been played as well} (12. d4 Bh3 13. Rb1 b6 14. Qa4 Bxg2 15. Kxg2
Ne7 16. Qb5 Qg6 {Black is doing great Abbasov-Marzolo, La Fere 2008}) (12. f3
exf3 13. exf3 {and now Black has logical positional play} Be6 $5 14. d4 Rad8
15. Bd2 {Byway-King, Morecambe 1981 now natural} Na5 $146 16. Qa4 b6 {would
secure pleasant position for Black with better chances.}) 12... b6 13. f3 {
now both games went 13...Ne5 which is also good move, but it seems} exf3 $1 {
might be even stronger} 14. Bxf3 {obviously} (14. exf3 $2 Ba6 15. Re1 Bd3 $17 {
it's not an option for White.}) 14... Ng4 $1 {this is the point of Black's
previous move. He forces favorable exchanges of minor pieces.} 15. Nxg4 Bxg4 {
and Black is just clearly better. Certainly Black knight is untouchable} 16.
Bxc6 $2 Rxe2 $1 {is winning for Black on the account of mating threats.}) 9...
h6 10. Ne3 {White's first choice by far. However, I would like to mention two
other moves:} (10. c5 {here I like} Qe7 11. Bf4 {I would prefer} Ne5 $5 $146 {
, although} (11... Qxc5 12. Bxc7 d5 {also reliable for Black as occurred in
Solovchuk-Kuzubov, Rivne 2016}) 12. b4 (12. Qd4 b6 {with idea} 13. Bxe4 Nc6 $1
14. Bxc6 dxc6 15. Rfe1 Bf5 16. Ne3 Bh3 $44 {with powerful compensation. White
will miss his light-squared bishop in defense .}) 12... b6 13. cxb6 axb6 14. Ne3
Bb7 {with comfortable play for Black. As usual white can't do much when the e4
pawn is supported so well.}) (10. b3 d6 11. Ne3 {see main line}) 10... d6 11.
Qc2 {The main move. Obviously White has alternatives:} ({After} 11. f4 {
we have an old classical game} exf3 12. exf3 Bd7 13. h3 Ne7 $1 {and Black
solved all opening problems in Lautier, J -Karpov, Biel 1990. This re-grouping
allows more flexibility to black pieces: for example, the knight can move to g6
or f5, while the bishop can assume its position on c6.}) (11. b3 {obviously we
have a very positional fight ahead and it's important to understand Black
ideas here. The following direction seems to me very logical} a5 {placing
pawns on dark-squares and restricting White's dark-squared bishop is an essential piece in a long-term battle.} 12. a4 b6 13. Qc2 Bb7 14. Nd5 {another example
} (14. Rd1 Ne5 15. Nd5 Nxd5 $1 {The queenside is pretty much locked therefore
Black can develop his play on the other side.} 16. cxd5 f5 17. c4 Qf6 18. Bb2
Rf8 19. Bd4 Rae8 $13 {Black is perfectly fine Moessle-Sedlacek, ICCF email 2007
}) 14... Nb8 $1 {A Very nice positional idea. Now Black is ready to capture on
d5.} 15. Rd1 Nbd7 16. h3 {another good example here} (16. Bf4 Nxd5 17. cxd5 Nf6
18. c4 Bc8 $1 {Black bishop was obviously misplaced on b7} 19. h3 Bf5 20. Be3
Nd7 21. Qc3 Nc5 22. Kh2 f6 23. Bd4 Qd7 $11 {with balanced position in
Balleer-Leupold, ICCF email 2008}) 16... Nc5 17. Be3 Bc6 18. Bd4 Nxd5 19. cxd5
Bd7 20. Rdb1 Qg5 $1 {draw agreed in Polugaevsky, L-Kholmov, R Moscow 1969 I
assume both players expected the following line} 21. b4 axb4 22. cxb4 Qxd5 23.
Bxc5 dxc5 24. bxc5 Qxc5 25. Qxc5 bxc5 26. a5 {and the arising endgame should
be drawish. It is easy to imagine a scenario where black blocks and captures
the a-pawn, while white takes two black pawns (c5 and e4 or c7)}) (11. Nd5 Bf5
12. b3 a5 13. a4 ({in case of} 13. h3 {Black can play} a4 $146 14. Be3 b6 {
with good game.}) 13... Ne5 {Worthy of consideration} (13... Nd7 14. Be3 b6 15.
Qc2 Bh7) 14. Be3 Nfd7 15. Bd4 Bh7 {Black has fully reliable position
Moskow-Gurevich,I New York 1992}) 11... a5 12. Rd1 ({Another line here is} 12.
a4 Qe7 13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. cxd5 Nb8 15. Be3 Bf5 {more than 20 games have been
played in this position, but nothing has been changed since classical encounter
} 16. h3 Nd7 17. c4 b6 18. Qc3 Nc5 $11 {Karpov-Kortschnoj, Baguio City 1978
which proved that Black position is extremely reliable.}) 12... b6 13. b3 Rb8 $1
{prepares 14...о ..e5} 14. a4 Ne5 15. Nd5 {in case of} (15. Bxe4 Nxc4 $1 16.
Bg2 Nxe3 17. Bxe3 Qe7 {Black has no problems whatsoever.}) 15... Nxd5 16. cxd5
f5 17. f3 {I believe this is White's best, as after} (17. c4 Qf6 18. Bb2 Bd7
19. Rac1 Re7 20. Re1 Rf8 21. Bd4 Qg5 $15 {I would evaluate Black chances
higher due to the possibility of seizing initiative on the kingside
Belchev-Vasilev, ICCF 2013}) 17... exf3 18. exf3 Qf6 19. Bd2 Bd7 20. c4 Re7 21.
Qc3 Qg6 22. Re1 Rbe8 $11 {with a balanced position Schoen-Freeman, ICCF email
2008. There would be little to play for in case of massive exchanges on the
e-file.} *

