1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 Bb4 {We are omitting Nc6 for now as d2-d4 is not a
threat and also because in case of Nc6 white can have an annoying resource
Nc3-d5.} 4. Bg2 O-O 5. Nf3 Re8 {This is considered to be an improved version
for Black since he did not commit to the о ..c6 move.} 6. O-O e4 {White has
two other knight's moves.} 7. Ng5 (7. Ne1 Bxc3 8. bxc3 (8. dxc3 {another line}
d6 {Black has an easy game here} 9. Nc2 Nbd7 {a good model game here is:} 10.
Ne3 b6 11. b3 a5 12. Nd5 Bb7 13. a4 h6 14. h3 {Anastasian,A (2520)-Gulko,B 
(2615) Yerevan 1996 and now Black could have played} Nh5 $1 {preparing the
solidifying f7-f5.} 15. Kh2 Nc5 16. Qc2 f5 $15 {with better prospects.}) 8...
d5 $1 {well-timed strike in the center} 9. cxd5 Qxd5 10. d3 {Other
possibilities:} (10. Nc2 Qh5 11. Ne3 Bh3 {a well-known idea in this kind of
pawn structure, as we have seen in one of the previous chapters.} 12. f3 Bxg2
13. Kxg2 Nbd7 $15 {and Black was doing great in Toma-Christiansen, Budva 2013.
Once again the e4 pawn is a thorn in white's heel.}) (10. d4 Qh5 11. f3 exf3
12. exf3 {Ibragimov-Lukacs, Budapest 1995 I found the following improvment
upon the game} Qa5 $1 $146 13. Bd2 {or} (13. Bb2 Be6 $15) 13... c5 {with very
convenient play for Black.}) 10... Nc6 11. Bf4 Qh5 12. dxe4 Nxe4 13. Qc2 Bf5
14. Qb2 {Koerholz-Becker, Trier 1998 Black should better played} g5 $1 $146 15.
Bxc7 Rac8 16. Qxb7 Qg6 $44 {with nice compensation. The point is that white's
dark-squared bishop has no good squares!}) 7... Bxc3 8. bxc3 {With this
recapture white intends to build up a strong center.} (8. dxc3 {This recapture
opens up the dark-squared bishop.} d6 9. f3 exf3 10. exf3 Nc6 {obviously Black
has no problems here, just one example} 11. Nh3 a5 $1 {planning to engulf the
c4 pawn with a5-a4, Na5 etc.} 12. Nf4 Ne5 13. b3 a4 14. Bb2 Bf5 {with an
excellent position for Black, Noeckler-Levushkina, Nuremberg 2011.}) 8... h6 9.
Nh3 d6 10. Nf4 ({in case of} 10. f3 exf3 11. exf3 {I like the following idea}
Be6 $146 12. d3 d5 13. cxd5 Nxd5 {with very active play. White's pawn
structure looks potent, but there are also a lot of weaknesses, such as e3 and
potentially d4 or c4.}) 10... Nbd7 11. d3 Nc5 12. Be3 Bf5 13. Bd4 {this
happened in Christiansen-Kraut, Germany 1995. After} exd3 $146 14. exd3 c6 {
Black's position is very comfortable. He just needs to maneuver his king's
knight to e5 and black would most likely have to part with his dark-squared
bishop, leaving him with no basis for an opening advantage whatsoever.} *

