1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 Bb4 4. Bg2 O-O {Besides 5. Nf3 move White has
important alternative} 5. e4 {which has been quite popular recently. Besides
White has tried many other moves, which are not very serious. I believe it's
quite important to mention} (5. e3 Bxc3 $1 {we have to capture on c3 before
White knight arrives to e2.} 6. bxc3 ({Unimpressive is} 6. dxc3 $2 e4 $1 {
Black is already better} 7. Ne2 Nc6 8. b3 Ne5 9. O-O d6 $17 {Black was clearly
better in Gavrilovic-Kojovic, Serbia 2006}) 6... Re8 7. e4 {other moves are
not impressive either} (7. d3 {obviously runs into} e4 $1 {with great position
for Black as he controls the important e4 square.}) ({After} 7. Ne2 {I like} c6
8. O-O d5 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. f4 {Mihajlov,S (2177)-Holm,K (2413) Norway 2016
Black should just have played} Nc6 $146 11. fxe5 Nxe5 12. Nd4 Bg4 13. Qb3 b6
$15 {with full control of the light squares.}) 7... c6 {Now we have position
from 5. e4 line with extra tempo for black. A good model game here} 8. Ne2 d5
9. exd5 cxd5 10. cxd5 Nxd5 11. O-O Nc6 12. Rb1 Rb8 $1 13. Qc2 Bg4 14. Qe4 {
Mysteriously draw was agreed in Arkell, K (2489)-Pert, N (2501) West Bromwich
2004, but objectively Black is clearly better after} Nf6 15. Qe3 Qd7 $17 {
White queen is awkward on e3 as well as the knight on e2 and the jobless
dark-squared bishop. Meanwhile, black is fully mobilized.}) 5... Bxc3 6. bxc3 {
White can also recapture with the other pawn} (6. dxc3 {This is a pet line of
Grandmaster Miezis. Overall it's pretty harmless, but Black has to be familiar
with the right plan.} Na6 $5 {I like this move, although Black can carry out
the same ideas through different move orders.} 7. Ne2 {Other options are :} (7.
Nh3 Nc5 8. f3 d6 9. O-O Be6 10. Qe2 h6 {it's important to establish control
over g5-square and thus to prevent possible о ..g5.} 11. Nf2 Nfd7 $1 {now
Black is ready to carry out f7-f5 idea.} 12. b3 a5 13. Nd1 $2 {obviously not
the best move. Better would have been} (13. Be3 f5 14. f4 exf4 15. Bxf4 Qf6 $11
{with equal game.}) 13... f5 14. exf5 Bxf5 15. Nf2 Qf6 $15 {and Black was
better in Miezis,N (2496)-Szoen,D (2440) Deizisau 2006 his plan includes о
Rae8, о Bg6 and etc.}) (7. Qe2 Nc5 8. Nh3 (8. b4 {leaves c4-pawn vulnerable.}
Na4 9. Qc2 Nb6 10. c5 Nc4 11. Qe2 b5 12. cxb6 Nxb6 13. Nf3 {has been played in
Rogule,L (2329)-Smirnov,A (2385)/Tallinn EST 2007 after natural} d6 $146 14.
O-O a5 $1 {I prefer Black due to vulnerability of White's queenside.}) 8... d6
9. f3 h6 10. O-O Be6 11. Nf2 {this position is covered via 7. Nh3 move order
}) 7... Nc5 8. Qc2 d6 9. h3 a5 10. O-O Be6 11. b3 Nfd7 {Black has fully
mobilized his pieces and now it's the suitable moment to advance the pawn to
f5.} 12. f4 a4 $1 {A very important resource. First white's rook should be
distracted from f-file.} 13. Be3 axb3 14. axb3 Rxa1 15. Rxa1 {And now it comes}
f5 $1 {and I was able to achieve comfortable game in Johansen-Avrukh, Olympiad
2004}) 6... c6 {with obvious idea to break in the center by means of d7-d5.} 7.
Nf3 {White's latest word in this line. It goes without saying White has a wide
choice here:} (7. Ne2 d5 8. cxd5 cxd5 9. exd5 Nxd5 10. O-O Nc6 {is comfortable
for Black. White has tried many moves here but can hardly pose Black any
problems.} 11. Rb1 (11. Qb3 Nb6 $1 12. d4 Be6 13. Qd1 Bd5 14. dxe5 Nxe5 15. Be3
Bxg2 16. Qxd8 Rfxd8 17. Kxg2 Nbc4 $15 {and Black was clearly better due to
White's damaged queenside pawn structure Zoltek, T (2345)-Farago, I (2505) Lodz
1980}) (11. d3 Bg4 $1 12. Bb2 (12. f3 $6 {is not a big fun for White} Bf5 13.
Kh1 Qd7 14. d4 exd4 15. cxd4 Rfe8 $17 {Black was clearly better in Hibbeler,
S-Abel, E Germany 1992. due to the weakening move f3.}) 12... Qd7 13. Re1 Rfd8
{and Black has much more comfortable game Claesen-Van den Doel, Belgium 2015.
The backward d3 pawn is definitely a source of worries for white. If it moves
to d4, then it will most likely become an isolated pawn.}) (11. d4 exd4 12.
Nxd4 {Piekarz, P-Rheinheimer, DDR 1989 Black should have forced simplifications
by means of} (12. cxd4 Bg4 {is just better for Black, as has been proven in
several games.}) 12... Nxc3 $146 13. Nxc6 Qxd1 14. Rxd1 Nxd1 15. Ba3 bxc6 16.
Rxd1 Be6 17. Bxf8 Kxf8 18. Bxc6 Rc8 {Black is slightly better considering the
pressure against the a-pawn, but White should hold without too much
difficulties.}) 11... Re8 12. d3 {Other moves are not impressive either} (12.
h3 {Yuffa,D (2510)-Alexeev,A (2301) Sochi 2017 Black should have reacted with
simple} Nb6 $1 $146 13. d4 Be6 $15 {with better game.}) (12. Re1 Rb8 13. Qc2
Be6 14. d3 Qd7 15. f4 Bh3 $17 {was clearly better for Black McClain-Herrera,
ICCF email 2005}) 12... Bg4 $1 {a thematic idea.} 13. f3 Bf5 (13... Bc8 $5 {
could be an interesting alternative. It would be worth it to waste a tempo to
provoke a weakening move f3.}) 14. Rxb7 Nb6 15. f4 e4 16. Qb3 $2 (16. dxe4 Bxe4
17. Qb3 {would maintain the balance.}) 16... Be6 17. Qb5 exd3 $19 {and White
was absolutely lost in Mamedyarov,S (2757)-Giri,A (2776) Doha 2014}) (7. Qb3 b6
8. Ne2 ({Black has easy game after} 8. d3 Na6 9. Ba3 Re8 10. Ne2 {three games
arrived at this position but Black has never played the mostnatural} Bb7 $146 {
following up with d7-d5 advance and a very comfortable game.}) 8... Bb7 9. d4
Re8 $1 10. dxe5 {I also checked} (10. Bg5 d6 11. O-O Nbd7 {and Black should be
fine. The pin can be easily broken with h6.}) 10... Rxe5 11. f4 $2 {Serious
mistake. Better would have been} (11. Bf4 Re8 12. Qc2 {although Black is more
than fine after} Na6 13. O-O Nc5 14. f3 Ba6 $1 {with a typical counterplay
against white's damaged pawn structure.}) 11... Rxe4 $1 {A typical exchange
sacrifice} 12. Bxe4 Nxe4 13. O-O c5 $1 $17 {with strategically winning
position for Black Schmidt, H-Fauth, H Germany 1992. White simply has nothing to
oppose the upcoming attack on the long diagonal h1-a8.}) (7. d4 exd4 8. Qxd4 {
White has also tried other moves:} ({First of all} 8. cxd4 $2 {is just bad in
the view of} Nxe4 $1 $17) (8. e5 Re8 9. cxd4 d6 10. f4 $2 {As much as four
games featured this move, which is actually a serious error.} ({White should
play} 10. Nf3 {with the following approximate line:} Nbd7 11. O-O dxe5 12. Nxe5
Nxe5 13. dxe5 Qxd1 14. Rxd1 Rxe5 15. Rb1 Re8 16. h3 {and White probably has
enough compensation for the pawn, but not more.}) 10... Be6 $1 {White is in
trouble. The f6 knight is untouchable in most of the lines due to exposed
white king.} 11. Qe2 {Another game saw} (11. Qd3 Nbd7 12. Qc3 dxe5 13. fxe5 c5
$19 {and White center is falling apart, together with his position in Troia, E 
(2304)-Horvath,A (2422) ICCF email 2003}) 11... Nbd7 12. Nf3 Nb6 13. c5 dxc5
14. dxc5 Bc4 15. Qd1 Qxd1+ 16. Kxd1 Na4 $17 {and Black wins at least a pawn
Kriksciunas-Christiansen, ICCF 2008}) {Now} 8... c5 $5 $146 {looks very
interesting, sacrificing a pawn for a few important development tempi.} 9. Qxc5
({Black faces no problems after} 9. Qd3 d6 10. Bf4 Nc6 11. Nf3 Re8 12. O-O Bg4)
9... Re8 10. f3 d6 11. Qe3 Be6 12. c5 dxc5 13. Qxc5 Nbd7 14. Qd4 Rc8 $44 {
with a very nice compensation and very active play.}) (7. Ba3 Re8 8. Qb3 ({
the idea to establish White dark-squared bishop on d6, doesn't work as
intended:} 8. Bd6 Re6 9. c5 b6 $1 10. Ne2 bxc5 11. Bxc5 Ba6 12. d3 d5 13. exd5
cxd5 14. O-O Nbd7 $15 {and Black is slightly better Serafimov-Shchekachev,
Paris 2005}) 8... b6 9. d3 ({The most logical alternative is} 9. Ne2 Bb7 10.
Bd6 {This idea fails to work} (10. O-O d5 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. exd5 Bxd5 {and
Black was already more comfortable in Singleton,M-Carlson,C USA 1978}) 10... c5
$1 11. d3 (11. Bxb8 $2 {runs into tactical} Bxe4 $1 12. Bxe4 Nxe4 $17 {with
clear edge for Black - white's bishop has nowhere to escape.}) 11... Nc6 12. f4
{all this happened in Blanco,H-Echeguren,G Argentina 1987, but Black missed a
very strong idea} Ng4 $1 $146 13. Bf3 Ne3 14. Kf2 Na5 $1 15. Qb1 f5 $1 {
and Black's initiative is decisive. After} 16. Kxe3 fxe4 17. Bxe4 Nxc4+ 18.
dxc4 exf4+ 19. Bxf4 Bxe4 {white king will be completely exposed.}) 9... Bb7 10.
Nf3 d5 11. Nd2 $8 dxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Bxe4 Nd7 {and Black successfully has
solved all opening problems in Sappinen, J-Rissanen, H Finland 1995}) 7... Nxe4
8. O-O ({Once White tried} 8. Nxe5 {but it shouldn't be so dangerous for Black}
Re8 9. d4 d6 10. Bxe4 dxe5 11. O-O {Jones, G (2645)-Gupta, A (2634) Reykjavik
2016 Here Black could have opted for} exd4 $146 12. Qc2 d3 $1 {A nice
intermezzo, intending to leave white with a bad pawn structure on the
queenside.} 13. Bxd3 g6 14. Bf4 Bh3 15. Rfe1 Nd7 {and upon completing his
development Black has no problems whatsoever.}) 8... d6 9. Nxe5 dxe5 10. Bxe4
Nd7 11. d4 Nf6 12. Bg2 exd4 13. cxd4 {this position has occurred in
Sekretaryov-Yaroshenko, ICCF email 2009 I would recommend here} Bg4 $146 14.
Qd3 Re8 15. Be3 Qd7 16. Rfe1 h6 {with a very reliable position for Black. It
would be desirable to exchange the light-squared bishops, which would lead to
equality.} *

